Civil rights groups issue travel warning for Missouri
Due to discriminatory policies and racist attacks in Missouri, the American Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) issued a travel warning to people of color who were preparing to travel to Missouri.
“The NAACP Missouri Travel Advisory, which took effect on August 28, 2017, calls for all African-American travelers, tourists, and Missourians to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling in Missouri due to a series of suspected racial incidents in Missouri in recent times,” the group’s statement said.
The recent passage of a Missouri law makes it harder to win discrimination lawsuits, and the state enforces laws to some extent against minorities, prompting the group to issue travel warnings.
Violations of civil rights are happening to people.
They were stopped for questioning, beaten or killed because of their skin color,” Missouri NAACP President Rod Chaber told The Kansas City Star.
“We have received many complaints, an unprecedented number.”
It was the first such warning issued by the group in the United States against a state.
The group cited racial defamation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tolly Sanders, a 28-year-old black Tennessee male.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year. He ran out of fuel while traveling in Missouri and was detained by Missouri police without charge for a crime.
The consultation also noted that a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General’s Office showed that “black drivers in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than whites.”
“The consultation was to raise awareness and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri,” Chaber said.
“People need to be prepared, whether it’s carrying bail to Missouri or letting relatives know they’re traveling in the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s Hate Crime Reporting Program, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015; the state ranked 16th in the nation, based on the number of crimes.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it more difficult to prosecute businesses for housing or employment discrimination.
U.S. states have passed immigration enforcement laws requiring local law enforcement to detain immigration violators, a move the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) said would increase the number of racial lawsuits and issued travel advisorys for Texas and Arizona.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the U.S. government against other countries, but recently, advisory groups have taken this approach to address certain laws and trends within the U.S.
