A picture to understand: the legal status of Bitcoin around the world
In addition to the price correction naturally caused by speculative properties, the sharp decline of this round of digital currency is also related to the "enemy" - regulatory risks.
From the visual map, the attitude of Eastern countries towards Bitcoin is more conservative than that of the West, and countries that account for the majority of the world are still waiting for the legitimacy of digital currencies, which represents the "black swan risk" is still very large.
*This article is from Wall Street News (WeChat ID:wallstreetcn), editor Wang Mu. For more information, please visit wallstreetcn.com or download the Wall Street News app.*
With the regulatory storm in major bitcoin markets such as China, South Korea and the European Union, the global digital currency led by Bitcoin has been bloodbathed this week, and the price of Bitcoin has fallen below the $10,000 psychological integer bit on Tuesday and the largest one-day decline in three years.
In addition to the price correction naturally triggered by speculative properties, the sharp decline of this round of digital currency is also related to the long-standing "enemy" - regulatory risks.
At this important juncture, visual big data website HowMuch.net has created a map showing the legitimacy and degree of regulation of Bitcoin in countries around the world.
As the following figure shows, green represents the legal market of Bitcoin; orange represents the neutral market, although it has not yet publicly legalized the status of Bitcoin, but there is no major use restriction; light pink represents the restricted market, that is, the local government tries to use the digital currency through red line policy or regulation; deep pink represents the country where Bitcoin is defined as illegal; gray is the country that has not yet commented.
(Photo by HowMuch.Net visualization team on January 15th)
The article pointed out that from the green color distribution in the figure, it can be seen that the traditional Eastern countries' attitude towards Bitcoin is more conservative than that of the West.
Russia is currently the largest country to define Bitcoin as illegal, China is one of the largest restricted markets for Bitcoin, and India is one of the largest countries that has not yet commented on Bitcoin and has not yet introduced relevant policies.
North America and Western Europe are the regions with the highest acceptance of Bitcoin, where the distribution of green blocks is more concentrated.
The views of countries in the Middle East and Latin America on Bitcoin are clearly divided, and the distribution of color blocks in these areas is more mixed.
Among them, Iraq, Iran, Turkey, Brazil are all legitimate bitcoin markets, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Bolivia and other countries have a certain degree of restrictions on their trading and use, and more Latin American countries have not yet voiced their voices on Bitcoin.
Combined with the above data, a total of 99 countries (or 40%) of the 246 countries in the world are not subject to restrictions on the transaction and use of Bitcoin, that is, green and orange areas.
Seven countries (or 3%) are restricted markets (light pink), 10 countries (or 4%) have defined Bitcoin as illegal (deep pink), and 130 countries (or 53%) have not treated digital currency information (grey).
This shows that countries that account for global entities (53%, more than half) are still waiting for the legitimacy of digital currencies led by Bitcoin in China, and also represent the “black swan risk” of Bitcoin, which is still very large, because some countries may eventually make legislative decisions to restrict digital currencies.
The article believes that global regulators have not yet fully understood the emerging category of digital currencies, which may be the main reason why most countries have not yet made a statement.
Although Bitcoin’s “pobility” has grown exponentially since last year and does not represent the interest of all countries, some countries may be concerned that local fiat currencies are under threat or that digital currencies are being used by criminal organizations.
Wall Street has written an article detailing the international regulatory news on bitcoin since last week, including China’s start to crack down on online platforms and mobile apps for centralized services on over-the-counter exchanges, South Korea’s ongoing consideration of closing digital currency exchanges, the European Union’s belief that bitcoin has not been widely accepted and warning investors of the risk of “losing their blood.”
Wall Street editor-in-chief selected "Reading News | 2018: Global Central Moms Open the Year of Digital Currency?" has mentioned that from any point of view of supervision, acceptance/criticism, and adoption, 2018 will become the first year of digital currency for global central banks.
Russia and other major countries criticize the legitimacy of Bitcoin, in fact, is also to give way to the official issuance of digital currency.
