Blocking critics on Facebook: If you can't stand the censure of voters, don't run for office
Our father understood the bad media style.
Americans love Washington, but soon after, the major newspapers began to lash out at everything he did, from domestic policy to political principles.
He was annoyed with these criticisms, no doubt.
But he did not silence these critics.
For as early as 1783, Washington said, “Freedom of speech is taken away—we are slaughtered like a lamb in silence and ignorance.”
It reminds me of Maryland Gov. Larry Hogan, who needs to learn from Washington.
Hogan’s staff blocked and deleted posts from at least 450 people because they posted their views on his official Facebook page.
The American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit against him earlier this week.
The governor’s staff described the lawsuit as hasty, and online coverage was rife with their strong resistance: “Who cares?”
A lot of people say, “It’s just Facebook.”
But this is important.
This is especially important because it is faced with people like Hogan.
It was a Republican who served as governor in a state that had a democratic majority, and he was surprisingly popular.
Among the 50 governors in the country, he received the second praise.
Hogan was not a reactionary impatience.
He was in good control of Maryland, strictly following the rules.
He is also very good at using Facebook as the main way to connect with voters, jokingly showing his baldness after chemotherapy for the first time on the homepage.
So it's completely unnecessary to block people who come to the governor's homepage for comments, and it's ultimately dangerous. The home page is a public forum, an official management platform that is blared by public tax-funded staff.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan’s spokeswoman, Amelia Shas, defended the governor’s actions, saying she thought blocking their comments was nothing more than trying to keep them restrained.
But they have too sloppyly described it as a flood beast or cynic who has swept the network.
The Washington Post spoke face-to-face with people who were blocked by Hogan.
They are nothing more than ordinary people talking to their chosen leaders: their status is a teacher, a small business owner, and a pastor, not a flood.
They have expressed their deepness, respect, and disquellence in their comments.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, calling on Hogan to remember his Catholic faith.
Bowie's barrister in Maryland, Rakshimi Salma Ramani, was not cynical, but she asked questions about hate crimes.
She wrote in the News Story Review section of The Washington Post, “I’m politely commenting that I’m disappointed that he didn’t respond to hate crimes and other recent news events.
I also don’t like a bunch of people commenting on the same topic, because they’re being ignored by some people, who are called herd mentality, not as a bunch of worried citizens.”
What the governor’s staff called a “dense spam bombardment” may seem to others to be “persistent.”
The Facebook era has made it easy to change a message, just blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It was also much cleaner than in the past, and to do the same in the past, it was necessary to send staff out to collect and burn newspapers with critical speech or to arrest or silence protesters.
But that’s what’s happening now, but on a digital level.
Hogan isn’t the first public official to be blamed for silving others on Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users because he blocked them on Twitter.
Last week’s landmark ruling in Virginia was about such a problem.
According to District Judge James C. Kacharis of Alexandria, the chairman of the Lawden County Oversight Committee blocked voters from her Facebook page in violation of the First Amendment.
Kentucky Governor Matt Bevin (R) is also patronized by the American Civil Liberties Union for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be so difficult.
In the Washington era, affordable postage and the Internet had similar influence.
The number of newspapers quadrupled between 1776 and 1800, and some wrote anonymous letters criticizing his leadership.
And even at that time, Washington had an anonymous flood of beasts against him.
People used pseudonyms such as Yurikra, Valerius, Belisarius, and Pogius to write to the newspaper to sharply criticize Washington's decision-making.
According to historical documents collected by the George Washington newspaper's online project, his office was inundated with petitions, criticizing his attitude on the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation between His Majesty the King of England and the United States of America, which he signed with England.
But he didn’t silence them.
Freedom of speech, political freedom, and freedom of speech are the foundation of this country.
Real leaders need to accept this.
