Poverty and Death in Kinzhu, Indonesia
Badtina DeJe didn’t use a stove when cooking.
She rarely even uses pots.
Her wooden house is located in Enarotali, the capital of Pania County, Papua, Indonesia, and the housewife usually just puts a sweet potato — locally called “nota” — directly into the fire.
Half an hour later, the charred sweet potato was taken out by a pair of hands that had not been washed, and devoured it.
Dai Jie sat on the mud floor—she had no furniture, and it was where she did everyday family chores, such as washing her clothes, and the water was very turbid, all from the nearby swamps.
In a room without a roof is a bucket, which is the outdoor toilet.
She was the youngest of the husband’s four wives, so she was not placed in the field to take care of her.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, it is dangerous to work until the evening: most of the men in the village are not working, and many are drunk, plus there are many soldiers here.
She said, "No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m.."
It was a rare glimpse into daily life in the Papuan highlands, once a Dutch colony that was incorporated into Indonesia after a 1969 referendum, but that referendum was also controversial when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by show off in front of the army occupying the area.
The current campaign to hold for independence and opposition to Dutch rule soon points the finger at the Jakarta government, which has imposed repressive rule in the region and isolated by foreign journalists and activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua provinces, while Papua New Guinea independently controlled the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is remote and deserted; it takes 90 minutes to fly from the provincial capital of Chayapura to Nabire, then rent a car for 5 hours and turn the river in your stomach.
There is no public transportation.
In this town of about 19,000 people, the wooden house is surrounded by bamboo fences, and the folded iron roof is a variety of yellow-brown coverings made of rust.
Few Indonesians have come in, not to mention journalists, and almost no foreigners.
Before the arrival of the Christian evangelist, the Mee Pago Papuans believed in a god named Uga Tamee.
There are other changes here as well.
Dai Jie said, "We're not used to these clothes." She was referring to her brightly colored hand-woven turban, dark shirt and bright skirt.
"We used to cover our bodies with only leaves."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, where 28 percent of the population lives below the poverty line and has the highest infant mortality rate and the lowest literacy rate in Asia.
But it is also the golden continent of Indonesia.
Panier County is located in the highlands, approximately the same area as New Jersey, with 153,000 people. The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grassberg, is just 60 miles from it, and the gold mine is owned by Phoenix-based Philip MacMoran Copper Gold.
In 2015 alone, Philips mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper mines here.
In addition, Papua is rich in wood resources, with an estimated value of $78 billion.
Yet these rich resources are also the source of the Papuan tragedy, and it is only by this fact that Indonesia’s powerful military forces have been able to suppress them.
A 2005 New York Times investigative report showed that Felipe paid nearly $20 million to local military and troops between 1998 and 2004, and $150,000 for an official alone.
Papuans’ demands for independence grew stronger, threatening the gold, and they were subjected to cruel treatment.
Since 1969, more than half a million Papuans have been killed and thousands raped, tortured and imprisoned by Indonesian forces, according to activists.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings in the Papuan tribal highlands of the 1970s have escalated into genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters.
A 2016 report by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Brisbane, “We Will Lose Everything,” included proofs of the previous year’s demonstrations of demarcance, such as extrajudicial executions, torture — another report that rape and electricity were particularly common — and the brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrations.
Andreas Halsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch, said that “violence happens every day, so it is difficult to count the number of victims”.
Papua's resources attracted large numbers of immigrants outside Indonesia, and the oppression began.
Eighty-three percent of the province's population of 3.5 million are Christians, but the demographics of Muslim economic immigrants have changed since they arrived from the densely populated islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra, and Sulawesi.
The Javanese food stall sells a mix of fried chicken and vegetables with peanut butter.
Locals are fighting.
Aposyu, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the provincial capital of Chayapura to find work, explained that “those immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than the local Papuans.
This has caused the local Papuans — the mama-mama — to lose their market.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo (often referred to as Jokowi) vowed on his 2014 campaign to address Papua’s inequality and abuse of power.
The former carpenter’s road to the presidential palace in Jakarta was supported by 27 of the 29 districts – including Panyia.
But Papua has nothing changed, and today the locals feel betrayed.
“We are heartbroken, we voted for Jokowi in 2014 and hope that he can achieve our wish and restore fairness.”
In fact, just two months after Jokowi took office in October, Paniai had his worst nightmare.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children in Enarotali sang Christmas carols in front of a bonfire outside, and two Indonesian soldiers suddenly rushed over on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Yavet Tebe, one of the soldiers was dissatisfied with their tone and then returned with four soldiers.
The victims and witnesses said the drunken soldiers used their guns to chase the children.
Then one of the soldiers fired at the children.
16-year-old Julianus Yemer was in a coma after being severely beaten.
Hours later, a raging fire broke out at the election commission building of a nearby government agency, and the incident escalated the next day.
Some 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered at a football field in front of the local police station and military command centre to demand justice.
They carried ritual bows and danced the waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua – running around the circle and imitating the birdsong.
Some protesters began throwing stones at military posts.
According to an official document seen by Time magazine, when emotions continued to intensify, the soldiers received orders through internal radio: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot immediately." But the document was not released to the local media.
Jeremias Kayamu, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighbourhood of Enarotali, felt imminent danger, and called for calm in the crowd and begged them to go home.
But no one was in the mood to hear him.
He stood on the porch of his brightly colored wooden house and told Time magazine, "When I turned back, my left wrist was suddenly shot."
Kayamu still doesn’t know who fired the gun, but he said the bullets came from among the assembled soldiers.
He added, "It was very crowded, they fired a lot of guns."
According to the cousins of local Olfius Yul, he witnessed the shooting and saw Orfius Juul in three shots.
Yuhanes sadly told Time magazine, “I ran over to check his body to see if it was him.
I found out he was dead...I kissed him."
Papua Police Chief Inspector Juje Mende told reporters that his subordinates were simply "protecting" the police station because the police station had been attacked.
In 2015, Papua police spokesman and police chief Pugio Sulistio said, “When someone threatens to kill us, we have to defend ourselves.”
It's a matter of death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
The next day news of the killing spread only slowly in Jakarta.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a speech in Cayapura expressing deep sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the abuse of power left over from Papua’s history.
“I hope that this case will be resolved as soon as possible, so that it will not happen again in the future.”
In October 2016, Security Minister Wilando said he wanted to set up a non-judicial mechanism to address the historical legacy of human rights violations.
But the excuses of the push also almost immediately sounded.
He said, “Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some were in the 90s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations, but it will still require a process.”
Then on June 5 in Jakarta, Vilando, in a conversation with Time magazine, said he had no plans to establish a complaint mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be settled in accordance with the law.”
The United Nations has filed a complaint against Wilando over the more than 1,000 deaths in the bloody independence vote in East Timor in 1999, but said 11 human rights violations in Papua have been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of the Pania incident sniffed at these statements.
“I’ve been interviewed four times in the last three years, but things haven’t progressed at all,” Yuhanes said.
Years later he said, "I'm tired."
He is still living in fear.
He said, “I’m scared.
I was afraid of being arrested by the army, afraid of being shot.”
His brother, Yucabos, also believed that the people of Paniai were afraid to talk about the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury the four victims.
He said, “After the body was buried, the military came to me.”
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in Deyai County, Paniai County.
A construction company manager refused to help transport a coma man to the hospital, where one person was killed and 17 injured, including a child.
A 24-year-old man, Lavianus Dovu, drowned while fishing in a nearby river and died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company's live office.
Police said villagers threw stones at police, so police fired warning shots.
But the riot-mobile unit (Indonesian paramilitary police) began shooting at the crowd, killing one.
Domingor Buddy, 29, told Time magazine, "We were all panicked and now were afraid they would take revenge." He lived near the hospital and witnessed the wounded being rushed to the hospital.
“I’ve been hiding at home for two days.”
The Deyai parliament has called for the police to be brought to justice and the riot mobile forces to be evacuated from the area.
Pania has always been a place of injustice to the Indonesian government.
The lack of effective development has led to the discontent of the Mee, Moni, Dani, and Damal tribes, which are scattered across the lush central highlands of Paniai.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of the Papuans by dispersing attacks and raids to kidnap Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top leaders of the Free Papuan movement were born in Paniai, including Tadius Yugi and Daniel Yudas Kogoa.
As a result, thousands of Panyias have been arrested by the military in recent years under the guise of “upholding national sovereignty” and deliberately detained.
Some have never appeared again.
In the eyes of the Papuans, Paniae was a “forgotten place of tragedy.”
Poverty breeds discontent.
Enarotali sells so little rice that the locals simply can’t afford.
The bread is out of reach.
The people here grow everything they can eat: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruits and leaves and vegetables.
Farming is a woman’s job, and every woman can take care of four or five sweet potatoes.
They usually use most of the harvest for writers, and the rest is sold in the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes are worth only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has been drawn among local Papuans and newcomers, and the number of these migrants has increased significantly since the opening of a new route to Nabire Airport.
A small amount of existing work usually falls into the hands of better-educated and wealthier immigrants.
Papuans have very little money or the necessary skills to run competitive companies.
John Gobai, President of the Paniai Tribal Council, said that “young people do not want to stay in this village ... because there is no work and no money.”
Papua is isolated from the world.
In addition, the restrictions on international media coverage remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudi and Basel Lonschamp were expelled from Papua because they “do not cooperate with the authorities,” even though they have been granted a rare license to shoot.
According to Felim Kane, Asia’s deputy director at Human Rights Watch, Jokowi’s election vow to lift reporting restrictions to promote transparency and development has not materialized.
In a statement, he said that “if foreign journalists try to cover the disaffected provinces of Papua and West Papua in the easternmost part of Indonesia, they are at new risk: denying visas and pulling them on the blacklist.”
The absence of media scrutiny means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua’s neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and the Solomon Islands — asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “all kinds of widespread human rights violations” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported the Free Papuan Movement .
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Almanata Nasir, who is indifferent to the group’s allegations, told Jakarta’s reporters that “Indonesia is still practicing democratic institutions and media freedom, so the evidence of human rights violations is difficult to hide.”
Locals want more attention from foreign governments.
According to a person familiar with the matter, on May 4, when the Dutch human rights ambassador, Kess Wan Barr, led a delegation of officials to visit Jayapura, the local people broke their silence and begged for "we want freedom." He also attended the meeting, but requested anonymity.
Indonesia will hold its next presidential election in 2019, but the Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
Gobai, the council’s president, said “Zokowi’s intentions were good, but he was surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shootings”.
He wanted Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai were not only living under the threat of a greedy army, but also of nothing, with few educations in the region and a lack of public health care.
Gobai said the Paniai people, like other Papuans, think that the vote they put on Jokowi is the debt he has to pay.
He said, “They don’t need money, they need justice.”
Even under threat and intimidation, the families of the Paniai victims made their last symbolic revolt: to bury the body of a victim across from the military police post.
They know that justice may never come, but at least they will not let those culprits forget their crimes.
Yukabos said with his head down, “My family was killed.
What else can we do?”
