Moore Beach tragedy: activists re-enact racist lynchings, justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury car runs through a group of onlookers in the small town of Monroe, Georgia, toward the tiny Moor Beach Bridge.
The car was carrying four black passengers and a white driver, and before the car reached the bridge, a group of white men with guns walked forward and blocked the road of the car.
The mob’s head — a middle-aged man in a fine-striped suit — took a deep sip of his cigar and glanced into the windshield.
The passengers in the car were full of fear.
“We want – Roger!” the man shouted.
“Get him out of the car!”
A young black man was dragged down the front passenger seat and screamed to break into silence.
Fortunately, the terrible scene of July 22 is just a repeat.
But when “Roger” put a noose around his neck, almost all the onlookers gave a real gasp.
Since 2005, civil rights activists have returned to the Moor Beach Bridge, recreating the scene of two black couples — Roger and Dorothy Malcon — along with Georges and Merey Dossy — hanged by the K.K. in 1946.
No one has ever been charged with murder.
“While we know who they are, even though we’ve seen them in the community, it’s incredible that none of them have been arrested in all these years,” said Tyron Brooks, who helped organize the re-enactment.
“This is the stain of history, a burden to our souls.”
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia lawmaker and lifelong activist.
For him, a repeat is a remarkable call to action, reminding the people of the Monroe community every year that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want to prosecute, we want to close the case, we want a cure, we want reconciliation, but we have to get justice first," he said.
“Unless we receive justice, we will not be healed or reconciled.”
On July 27, 1946, the coroner put a bed linen on the body of a victim of a lynching in Moore's Beach.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties are suspected of involvement in the lynching.
None of them have been prosecuted.
While the suspects have been at large for decades, civil rights activists say the dual motivation for lynching is well known throughout the town: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote in the primary for the first time later that summer.
According to FBI statistics, around the same time, black tycooner Roger Malcolm assassinated white landowner Barnett Hurst in a fight — it looked like it was for a woman.
Brooks said the town was rumored to be Hirst sleeping with Malcolm's wife Dorothy, and that her baby was not her husband's.
The FBI said that on July 25, 1946, the prominent white landowner, Roy Harrison, spent $600 to release Malcolm on bail.
Dorothy and his cousins, Mai Merry, and George Dorsey accompanied him to prison.
But as they returned from prison and were about to reach the Moore Beach Bridge, a group of lynching thugs surrounded the car.
“It turned out that it was Harrison who organized and ordered the execution of this murder,” an FBI report concluded.
“It is clear that there is a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement, who not only participated in the murder, destroyed the evidence, but also concealed the identity of the witness.”
Brooks is very brief.
He said, “This is a voting rights tragedy.”
“They were killed in a message that the killers sent to the black people of this community: ‘If you register and vote, you’re going to end up in the same way.’
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has been leading an annual re-enactment of the Mor Beach Bridge lynchings.
Her expression is vivid and gripping, with a deep racist background. Many people hope that this racism no longer exists in the United States.
It’s hard to look, it’s harder not to look, but Greene says that’s the point.
“We don’t want to talk about lynching because lynchings make us face the ugly side of everyone,” she said.
“But if you don’t listen to me or if you don’t hear me talk about my own experience, I can’t have a relationship with you.”
This year’s show began in June, with nearly 30 actors — a dozen whites and the rest black — huddled in a room on the first day to listen to an overview of Green’s rehearsed show.
Wade Malbow is co-director of Green.
He has been playing the K-K role for years, but he says the role is never easy.
“I feel dirty because I’m not that kind of person,” Malbow said.
“But I think it’s very important to keep this history alive, because we don’t want to go back to that era.”
In the room, actors Darius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who played Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hirst, were rehearsing their lines.
At the beginning of the show, Malcolm yelled and pushed away Hirst, angry at his sleeping wife Dorothy.
“I said, get out of my place!”
Rascona shot back.
And then they fought.
Then everyone (at least all the black actors) burst out laughing.
Green laughed the most.
“What’s wrong?!” asked Rascona.
He was panicked and confused.
Have I played too much?
“No,” Green said with a laugh.
"I just don't think white people will say 'ah' when they hit back."
“Yes,” another black actor quipped.
"Your tone must be tough."
In this way, the energy in the room changed; the feeling of fraternity drove away the discomfort.
Everyone worked hard to do this, not only to perform the play, but also to commemorate the four victims.
The place begins again.
This time, when Rascona said this "ah", the tone was sharp and powerful.
No one laughs.
The re-enactment ended strongly and quickly.
Screams, gunshots, and then there was silence.
A woman dressed in funeral black stood by the actor’s body and sang Billy Hallede’s mourning “Strange Fruit.”
Her voice pressed against other words.
A hundred yards away, about forty spectators were constantly wiping sweat and tears.
Blacks and whites accounted for almost half of the audience.
There are a couple who come to see the show from Ithaca, New York, and many people live near the road.
Brooks took them to the cemetery of Malcolm and Dorothy for a feror, and nearly eight hours later, everyone was suffering from Georgia's uncomfortable feeling of humid heat.
Until then, the murderer was still a fan. But now, standing in the same land where the lynching took place, there was anxiety in the air.
When the song’s final note disappears, Green asks people to approach some to check the body of the actor.
The children leaned over, looked at the false blood and corpses, and whispered to each other.
“They’re not really dead,” a little boy muttered, as if reminding himself.
A few minutes later, Green thanked the crowd and then the show ended.
The actor brushed the lynching rope and wiped away his tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marlbow, a suit man who plays the head of the Three K parties.
Nick Rasconner hugged two of his colleagues and wept in their arms; the emotion in the show eventually infected him.
“It doesn’t matter,” one of the women whispered.
“We know that’s not the case in your heart.
You do it for a reason."
After that, the audience sat down to have dinner with the actors.
At the same table, a white couple from Atlanta chatted intimately with a black couple they had just met, talking about a repeat.
It was difficult for Dennis Duplinsky to find words to describe how she felt after watching.
“It’s hard to imagine those horrible words and actions ... that people like you say and do it because they look like you,” she said.
“It really made me think that the lynching was still going on,” she added, “and now this kind of thing is only called a police shooting.”
In the room, Tyrone Brooks sat at the table watching, tasting and reminiscing about civil rights.
He said he had already started planning for next year’s show.
“Reuncoming is an inspiring way because it describes the horrors we’ve been through, but it’s also very educational,” he said.
“If you don’t learn from it, it could happen again.
Those who do not study and do not know their own history are doomed to repeat them.”
