Scientists at China's Air Force Engineering University study laser satellite for removing space junk
Reference News Network reported on January 18 that Chinese scientists have put forward a bold and innovative proposal to use large lasers to clean up cluttered Earth orbit, destroying old satellites and their sky litter.
According to the US "Newsweek" website reported on January 15, the researchers of the Chinese Air Force Engineering University wrote a paper entitled "Space-based laser removal small-scale space debris re-orbiting model study", the paper describes how by the use of space-based platform lasers, space debris can be irradated into smaller, less harmful debris.
Space junk has been a concern for the International Space Agency for years, and NASA has considered a variety of options to track, detect and remove man-made debris.
The way large-scale space debris is removed includes a giant network for cleaning and collecting waste, as well as magnets that can be used to suck them out of orbit. Chinese scientists have conducted laser simulation studies and concluded that this will be an effective way to clean up Earth's orbit.
The abstract of the paper states: “(simulation studies) provide the necessary theoretical basis for the application of space-based platform laser removal space debris technology.”
A 2014 study by U.S. defense giant Lockheed Martin found that there are about 200 threats a day for satellites that are orbiting.
High-speed debris moving along Earth's orbit is seen as a serious threat to future space missions, described by European Space Agency experts as a "deadly cascade of threats." High-speed debris has continued to increase over the past year.
According to the U.S. "Popular Machinery" monthly website reported on January 17, space is basically empty, but the space next to Earth is becoming more and more crowded. Every satellite we send into space will eventually become another piece of debris orbiting the Earth, and over time, these debris will pile up.
The more debris there are, the higher the chance that a satellite that is still functioning will be hit by the debris, which in turn will damage or destroy a multimillion-dollar investment.
All space agencies have plans to remove space junk in the future.
NASA is considering using jet gas to reduce the speed of debris, de-orbiting it, and Europe is considering launching a satellite carrying a large net to capture debris and bring it back to Earth, and Japan's idea is to capture the debris with an electric chain.
Right now, China is also proposing a solution to space junk, using a large laser to hit floating space junk into less harmful small pieces.
According to a paper published in the German journal Optics by a group of researchers at the China Air Force Engineering University, installing such a laser on a satellite would be enough to clean up space effectively, at least according to the simulation.
The only way to prove its effectiveness is to test it, and there are no arrangements for such a mission, but it may be sooner or later that someone will install a laser on a satellite and send it into space.
Once that’s done, we can finally start eliminating the problem of space junk once and for all.
(Compilation/Hu Jing, Wang Haiyu)
