Latest results of age assessment test for asylum seekers in Sweden announced
The Swedish asylum-seekers test uses the latest method to medically assess their age, and the latest results show that more than 80% of the subjects were judged to be over 18 years old, but not all people believe in their accuracy.
The Swedish National Forensic Science Centre (R?ttsmedicinalverket) began the test earlier this year.
After being accused of failing to accurately assess the age of some of the refugees claiming to be minors, the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) designed the tests to allow for a more accurate age assessment during the asylum process.
To date, the Swedish Migration Board has sent 6,880 testers, and the Forensic Medicine Center has released the results of a total of 2,481 testers between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty per cent (2002 persons) were sentenced to be 18 years of age or older, but in another 25 tests, the Swedish National Forensic Science Centre determined that the subject “may be 18 years of age or older.”
In 432 tests, the result was that the person “may not be under the age of 18.”
The test is only for people with age questions.
According to John Granson of the Center for Forensic Medicine, these results are consistent with those of the previous months.
He told The Local: “There is not much difference between this data and the data of previous months, and the numbers are very consistent.”
The higher percentage of cases judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that these asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the center released 581 test results and said there were 442 “inspects that the subject was 18 years of age or older.”
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated the 581 test results and found that 243 of them had publicly stated that they would be 18 years old this year.
X-rays of the wisdom teeth, MRI scans of joints, and then analysis by dentists and radiologists, are also questioned in some areas.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at Caroline College, whose work includes assessing people’s biological maturity to determine whether they experienced puberty earlier or later than normal age.
He told the newspaper Metro: “I have reason to think that, and I think the measurement used shouldn’t be that way.
It is very inaccurate to determine the biological age in this way.
If we can't guarantee accuracy, we shouldn't pretend we can do it."
However, the Forensic Science Center's Glandson defended the accuracy of these tests: "In general, there is little risk that a child will be judged to be an adult."
The biggest risk is that the person is just under the age of 18, which is about 10%.
