How did the football financial rules affect Neymar's move to Paris?
The rules aimed at preventing unrestricted spending by European luxury football clubs will not prevent Neymar from moving from Barcelona in Spain to Paris Football Club (PSG) in France at a record price.
The result is a further relegation of Paris's St. Germain Football Club by the Union of European Football Associations (UEFA). The European Football Association is the governing body of European football, which has the right to ban teams from participating in the widely watched Champions League.
The 2011 UEFA Financial Fair Play Rules (FFP) means that Paris Saint-Germain Football Club will eventually have to prove that Neymar’s transfer was funded without causing a huge loss.
FC Barcelona has paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to pay for the Brazilian player’s untos, while Neymar’s salary will be as high as tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial implications of Neymar’s move to France.
Considering that the team’s funding came from the financially coarse Qatari ruling family, Paris Saint-Germain Football Club could certainly sign Neymar in cash and include him in the ranks of other stars.
Clubs can spend a lot of money to buy players, but they have to use their legal sources of income to make up for the huge sums of money they spend to break even in football-related businesses.
The Financial Fair Play Rules were conceived by Michel Platini after he was elected UEFA president in 2007.
The former French player believes that for clubs that are heavily indebted in pursuit of success, if the bank or everyone withdraws their support funds, they are actually cheating and putting the club at risk of destruction.
In 2011, the Rules shifted from club debt issues to club loss monitoring.
The change means that the business model that Roma Abramovich used when he bought Chelsea in 2003 to buy a club with potential, and then spend a lot of money to improve the team and build a global brand, now facing a more demanding situation.
During the three-year Rules assessment period to 2018, the club is likely to lose €30 million.
Despite Abu’s debasement by his then-president in 2015, UEFA’s successor, Aleksander Ceferin, remains committed to stopping excessive spending.
“Of course the Rules have not yet lapsed, and we will certainly strengthen the regulations of the future,” Andrea Traverso, who is in charge of the rules-related matters at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
While Paris Saint-Germain Football Club will pay Neymar’s buyout terms at one time, it can also be distributed within the duration of the contract based on the amount of the accounting purpose.
Neymar has signed a five-year agreement, so the transfer fee may be shown as a fee of 44.4 million euros in the annual account for the next five years.
The first wave of Rules sanctions imposed in 2014 imposed the toughest sanctions on Paris Saint-Germain and the Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City club.
Paris Saint-Germain Football Club was fined 60 million euros ($82 million at the time), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and asked the team to reduce the number of players to 21 players in the 2014-15 season, instead of the normal 25 players.
UEFA is staring at clubs that try to increase their income by pegging to their owners and deceiving financial regulators.
While Qatari companies can sponsor Paris Saint-Germain Football Club, UEFA will not consider it a legitimate income if the amount of sponsorship is considered to exceed standard market prices.
This is what happened in 2014 when UEFA ruled at the time that the amount of money the Qatar Tourist Board sponsored by Paris Saint-Germain Football Club was overstated.
According to reports, a part of Neymar's income from Paris Saint-Germain football club may come from payments made by the 2022 Qatar World Cup Organizing Committee.
But Paris’s Saint-Germain football club and the organizing committee have denied that Neymar will be the World Cup ambassador, and it’s easy for UEFA’s regulators to do so.
The recent sanctions imposed on Paris’s Saint-Germain football club mean that UEFA will be more wary of any attempt to circumvent the rules.
On Thursday, people familiar with the matter said that UEFA had not held advance discussions with Paris Saint-Germain Football Club about Neymar's transfer.
The individuals were contacted only by the Associated Press on an unnamed name because they were not authorized to discuss the situation of the Paris Saint-Germain football club.
The last published accounts show that Paris Saint-Germain had operating income of €542.4 million in 2015-16, with a profit of more than €10 million.
The accounts for the previous fiscal year have not yet been published.
Paris Saint-Germain Football Club expects Neymar’s joining will bring a boon to sponsorship events, franchises and jersey sales.
The club expects revenue to grow by at least 30 percent after signing Neymar.
It is clear that seeing one of the most famous players leave, the Spanish league is deeply angry, trying to hinder Neymar's move and claiming that Paris Saint-Germain Football Club violated the Rules.
La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS that "this is a clear illustration of a 'financial doping', with clubs and countries alike", referring to Qatar, which has ultimate ownership of Paris's Saint-Germain football club.
Arsenal team (all of the club's owners are American sports tycoon) head coach Arsene Wenger, with reservations about the attitude of state-funded clubs with La Liga.
“It’s a consequence of ownership, and it’s revolutionized the entire ecology of football over the last 15 years,” Wenger said on Thursday.
“Once the country has a club, everything happens.
This will make it very difficult to comply with the Rules, because for a country there are many different ways or interests to require big-name players to represent a country.”
