Bank of England to maintain interest rate of 0.25%
The Bank of England will announce at a later date that interest rates will remain unchanged, after weak economic growth and easy inflation have dashed hopes of an upward hike.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue to be “weak” as it tightens interest rates while tightening household incomes.
Policymakers at the bank’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to maintain interest rates at 0.25 percent, while a handful of members this month called for higher interest rates, even as weak economic growth has weakened the boost.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank of England shrunk its growth forecast for 2017 and 2018 to 1.7% and 1.6%, respectively, and warned that the household income crunch will continue, while inflation will skyrocket to nearly 3% in the autumn.
But it said interest rates would need to be raised over the next few years to curb inflation from Brexit, while borrowing costs could need to rise more sharply in the financial markets.
Large-scale economic promotion policies were implemented a year ago by the effects of Brexit, and members voted to withdraw them.
The Bank of England will announce a halt to its regular financing scheme, which will start providing cheap funding to banks in February, although the bank said under the plan it now needs to add an additional £15 billion to a £115 billion.
In the minutes of the interest rate decision-making meeting, the Bank of England said: “In the core forecast of the MPC, gross domestic product (GDP) remains weak in the near term, as tighter real household incomes will continue to suppress consumption.”
With regard to interest rates, the bank has repeatedly reiterated the need for “some monetary policy tightening” to suppress inflation, and it needs to be “greater” than market expectations.
The market is currently expected to achieve its first growth in the third quarter of next year and the second in 2020.
But the bank stressed that any call-up would be “slow” and “restrained.”
The bank’s growth forecast for this year and next is on a downward trend, compared with a forecast of 1.9% and 1.7% in May.
The bank maintained its forecast of 1.8% growth in 2018.
The British pound fell against the dollar, and the euro followed suit.
The British pound fell 0.5% against the dollar to 1.31, while the euro fell 0.4% to 1.11.
Prior to the change in the decision, rising expectations were dashed by recent unwarranted growth data. GDP rose to 0.3% in the second quarter, compared with just 0.2% in the previous three months.
The bank said growth in the third quarter was likely to remain at 0.3 percent, although it would rise slightly at the end of the year.
