The National Health Service (NHS) has a green light for controversial HIV drugs.
After the High Court settles the dust for NHS drug funding, patients will be able to receive “transformative” HIV prevention treatment from September.
The NHS England has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a drug that can be taken before sex, has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in high-risk groups by about 86 per cent. Health services will now provide the drug to an estimated 10,000 people through a three-year initial trial.
It agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld the High Court ruling last year. The ruling said the NHS was entitled to pay PrEP for the cost of the drug, despite the NHS's claim that local authorities should fund the drug.
The move announced on Thursday was described by British NHS chief Simon Stevens as a "major new intervention", while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) described it as a "critical moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to be registered. More clinics will be added in October, followed by full implementation in England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medication taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Trials have shown that PrEP can significantly reduce HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means there are enough specific medications in the human body to prevent HIV infection.
This medication can be taken daily or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay, bisexual men, transgender people, and those who have not successfully received treatment.
The clinic will determine whether participants who are eligible and consent to the trial, including men, women, transgender people, and their sexual partners who are in an HIV status with an unknown person who has received antiretroviral treatment.
Those who live in England and register as general practitioners can also sign up at the sexual health clinic they attend locally.
The scheme will cost £10m, while the NHS England branch has signed a contract to procure the drugs this week after making an international competitive procurement.
The trial aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence about how it is positioned, absorbed and implemented on a large sample basis.
Mr Stevens said: “This significant new intervention should complement and reinforce HIV prevention broadly and increasingly successfully.
This is another milestone in more than 30 years of action that deserves progress in addressing the major health challenges of humanity.”
Dipola King, chief executive of the UK AIDS Trust (NAT), said: “This is a critical moment in the fight against AIDS.
If it does target people in need and at risk, pre-exposure prophylaxis offers the possibility of changing the UK AIDS epidemic.
Starting in September, people at high risk of HIV will receive a new, approved tool through the NHS-funded trial in England that can be implemented alone, without consultation with sexual partners, which will bring improvement to the lives of many people.
We are in favor of this announcement with both hands.”
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terence Higgins Trust, said: “The first priority now is to ensure that trials are pushed away rapidly across the country and that no one living with HIV can fall behind.
Now that we have purchased the PrEP trial drug, we are ready to protect more than 10,000 people at high risk of HIV.”
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “After months of delays and delays in the government, the start of the PrEP test is very popular and should come sooner.”
Evidence shows how this drug can change as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stop spreading this deadly infectious disease.
This trial will allow us to further and fully understand the advantages of PrEP.
It is now important to roll out the trial as soon as possible across the country to protect people exposed to HIV and to help us further end the spread of HIV in society.”
