High quality of life: the application of the loft and clever design to make the small apartment of the Count's Palace into a spacious home
Joanne Ray was a former banker who was keen to renovate the house, and in 2014 she moved from a large house on Knightsbridge to a small apartment in the Count's Palace.
This apartment is located on the first floor of an elegant Queen Anne-style terrace – Joanne didn’t pack her bags to sell it, which is a strong proof of the new design.
“Before that, I was living with my ex-boyfriend in a larger house on Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
“I was looking for the right house with an offer.
I saw this apartment in the Count's Palace, and its ceiling was high.
I made a big offer that day.”
Since first looking at the room, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has now been completely overhauled.
The apartment was originally a complex single room — requiring a walk through the kitchen to walk to the bedroom — and Joanne wanted to add storage space and loft to make the most of the ceiling height.
“I want high ceilings, big windows, plenty of light.
That’s what I ask for,” she said.
To do this, she hired Elvan Azadi from Duck & Shed's architecture and design studio (located in Notting Hill) to use the 12.5-foot ceiling to build a home. The home is not only a development, but also a place where Joanne lives.
The ceiling is not high enough to add two up-and-down spaces, so the architectural challenge is to create a loft that is high enough for people to stand.
Erfan must be creative in mind so that he can solve this problem.
“Steel structures are quite complex,” he explained.
“We have to arrange the space so that it is displayed up and down, and there is no need to shrug the back of the shoulder.
It is not only as simple as building a simple platform, but also to start these steels to put them at the appropriate height of the realization of functions.”
Through this arrangement, Erfan was able to get two full-body high rooms in the space—with many interesting elements added.
The loft features retro copper windows under the Retrouvius brand overlooking the charming living area.
The golden furniture with mirrors, small silver furniture and Serge Mouille retro lighting laid the overall style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in increasing the atmosphere, space and light.
A mirror is mounted at both ends of the short corridor that can make it look longer.
In the kitchen, a splash-proof plate with a mirror is like a window leading to another room.
At the porchy, small plaids with mirrors provide Joanne with storage space for tableware and glassware.
The beautiful living room has a fascinating sense of space that can be put away when the kitchen is not in use.
The kitchen is not new.
But what’s unique about this folding kitchen is a garage-style lift door.
“There’s some knowledge of engineering here,” Elvan explains the reinforced veneer MDF door.
“It’s a balancing principle, so it’s easy to slide when you push the door.”
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage, Joanne got an additional 16 square meters, an extra bedroom, and an improved layout.
“Eventually, what you sell is the size of the home — or your valuation is based on the size of the home,” Erfan said.
“Basically, real estate agents walk into the room and calculate it based on the size of the floor.”
They will try to increase the footprint of the space, while using high-quality materials, thus bringing a sense of luxury to this space.
“The material is your own choice, and therefore helps create an emotional bond in your home,” Elvan said.
“You’re not going to love the power on the wall.
These things are important, but they won't hold your heart."
It turns out that with good design and an extra area, standard apartments can be shaken to make you marvel.
In fact, you might choose to live like Joanne.
