Two brothers stage a $500 million real estate empire battle
Forty years after the founding of the Italian family, the two brothers fought for one of Victoria’s largest real estate empires worth more than $500 million.
Colin De Lutis, a former Carlton Football Club director and developer, lives in a mansion in the Tukala district, while the three gates are located at the residence of his brother Paul. The latter took him to the Supreme Court for the division of their real estate and business assets.
Paul has wanted to leave the family business since 2014, but the two brothers have been in a heated debate on the separation of assets in the Supreme Court.
The brothers and their mother owned a total of 38 real estate properties worth more than $500 million, which have been accumulated since the family bought Smith Street in the Collingwood district in 1973.
There, the family founded the Westco Jeans Company and gradually grew to the size of 160 retail chains.
In 1999, the company sold for $85 million.
After that, the money was invested in real estate. Currently, the De Rutis family's portfolio includes city office buildings, Brunswick and Sorrento developments, Gold Coast and Bühler Hill apartments, and suburban shopping centers.
Under an agreement with his late father, Colin, who was described by his brother Paul as the "primary promoter and dominant figure" of the De Rutis family, had about two-thirds of the company's assets, while Paul accounted for about one-third.
Documents submitted to the court state that, after conversion, Colin owned property worth $316 million, while Paul owned property worth $17.6 million.
Paul came to believe that the division of real estate and cash proved to be the crux of the negotiations.
“Colin’s proposal for a division of property left him what I thought was the best property,” he wrote in a first court affidavit in 2015.
On Friday, the Supreme Court held its first hearing after several failed mediations.
Now, the two brothers are still fighting for control of the existing business, and Paul says Colin has kicked him out.
Colin denied this and accused Paul of poor management of certain real estate.
In an early affidavit submitted by Colin, he expressed a desire to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian tradition dictates that family is the most important option. My Italian descent determines that family is the most important option," he wrote.
The cost of the case continues to rise, along with hundreds of pages of affidavits, emails, corporate reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, Charter Keck Cramer, Allan Myers, QC and other top law firms, as well as senior lawyers hired by both parties.
Ms. de Rutis and her late husband, Luigi, were both Italian immigrants. They have been operating mass and deli since the late 1950s, and bought a shop in Braunschig in the early 1970s.
They used collateral to buy the Collingwood property, where Colin opened the family’s first jeans store.
Colin said, “I was in high school when I was in high school,” and he started Westco there, “when Paul was still very young (about 10 years old).”
Anna de Rutis said she and Luigi, who died in 2012, want to be able to pass on property to her son in peace.
“Luigi used to say to me that he would never want his brothers to end up in court,” she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, were no longer members of the De Rutis Group of Companies, and Colin said Mark paid him $10 million and $26 million to Luke when he left the company.
Paul said both Luke and Mark were “dissatisfied with the division of their property.”
According to TV star Eddie McGuire, who kept a low profile despite being a member of the former AFL club’s biography in 2015.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul on Friday, along with their lawyers.
However, only Colin responded via text message. He said that because the case had been brought to court, "I really can't say much."
“It was very, very sad that my brother Paul chose to prosecute me and bring our family affairs to court,” he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a court filing that he had tried to meet his brother’s demands.
“Our father doesn’t want to see Paul and me finally have a current dispute,” he said, adding that he “remains hopeful that the dispute will be resolved.”
On Friday, that hope seemed to be dashed.
“Our problems will be resolved through the courts in the near future,” Colin wrote.
