Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the president's media time
Others have tried, but all have failed.
John F. Kelly might actually be able to do that.
If that’s the case, then he’s the first.
According to Politico, a U.S. political news website, the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to President Trump — including news media reports — to keep big bosses more stable.
Here is a quote from journalist Josh Dorsey:
“As the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, began his first day of work to gather discussions with senior officials, he pointed to a major problem for President Trump to be in the White House: bad information flowing into the president’s hands.”
Kelly told the officials that receiving good information helps the president make better decisions, so the information needs to be in his hands — in both written and briefing form.
Kelly’s diagnosis looked like a muting one, but others tried to tame it by spying on Trump’s media time, but all ended in failure.
President Trump’s TV addiction has been around for a long time — and now in the White House, his habit of watching TV is deepening.
In February, former campaign adviser Sam Nenberg told Politico: “If candidate Trump is frustrated with unfair reporting, it would be helpful to let him know that he has received positive coverage on a credible channel.”
Tala Palmeri of Politico wrote at the time that “based on the experience of six former campaign officials, the point in controlling Trump’s Twitter habit is to ensure that the media messages he receives have always included some praise.”
This is completely no problem.
But Trump’s Twitter habit used to be “controlled” that the view is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaign officials know something we don’t know about — that is, if there isn’t any intervention by them, Trump’s tweets will be even more fiery.
We may never have known about the tweets that Trump didn’t send.
If his clerks were able to save him from the water and fire, even if only a few times, their efforts would be worth it.
But no one has been able to stop Trump from causing controversy.
Part of the problem is that in a White House of competing groups, people are pushing their careers by delivering potentially or unreliable data to Trump that may be reliable and unreliable.
Politico — all about the story — reported in May that advisers were hobbling about strategically providing suspicious information to the president.
This is an example described by journalist Shane Goodmancher:
“Current and former Trump officials say Trump’s reaction to negative news footage such as a volcanic eruption, especially as destructive information leaks, he would frantically want to find out where it came from.
At the end of February, an article on the website of the cyber instigator Charles C. Johnson, GotNews.com, was copied to the president, accusing Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the “source of a large amount of information leak” at the White House, as Trump did at the time.
Even though Johnson had been permanently banned from Twitter for harassment, he had provided no concrete evidence, and he had blown up a large number of false controls, which he later publicly denied.
Trump read the article and began asking officials about Walsh’s situation.”
Goodmancher also said that then-chief of staff Reins Pribas and White House secretary Rob Porter “had tried to build a system to manage and document documents that Trump received.”
What about the result?
Kelly was going to do the same, in three months.
He may prove that he is a more efficient manager than Pribas, but Trump is still the impulsive Trump, and his aides are still competing against each other for influence.
These timeless influencing factors can make Kelly’s mission more difficult.
