Italy takes tough stance on NGO migrant rescue boats
Italy has issued a warning to non-governmental organizations operating migrant rescue boats in the Mediterranean that they will not be allowed to continue to implement rescues if they do not sign new rules for managing operations.
In an interview with the Turin daily News, the Minister of the Interior, Marco Minetti, said: “If NGOs do not sign new norms of conduct, it is difficult to see how they will continue”.
The warning came a day after Italian officials detained a German aid group, the crew of a boat, who was suspected of collaborating with human traffickers to help illegal immigrants.
The aid group, which operated for just one year, declined to comment on the specific theme of the charges against Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
In a social media statement, the organization said, “For us, saving lives is and will be the most important thing for us now, so we regret that we are not currently operating in the search and rescue zone.”
“After collecting all the information, we can only assess all allegations and situations at this time.”
Italian officials have been monitoring the Youth Rescue ship Iuventa since October.
Its crews are suspected of carrying human traffickers directly from small boats to transport migrants, and allowing smugglers to flee hastily and re-use the ship.
According to prosecutors' documents, at least one such meeting allegedly took place at sea 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast. The document was published by Italian media.
Its crew is suspected of blatant disregard for the authority of the Italian Coast Guard, which oversaw rescue operations in the area out of humanitarian enthusiasm and not for any other motive.
According to the code of conduct, ships such as Iuventa clearly need an Italian police officer to supervise their activities on board.
Currently, only three of the nine NGOs involved in the search and rescue operation have agreed to comply with the Code of Conduct: Save the Children, the Malta-based Migrants’ Maritime Assistance Station and the Pro-Activa Open Arms in Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it did not consider the new rules, if necessary, to be acceptable because they did not bring any "significant changes and obstacles" to its rescue operations.
Among the organizations that refused to sign were the Nobel Prize-winning organization Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp drop in the number of migrants arriving in Italy in recent weeks showed that efforts to strengthen Libyan coastal guards and unite local mayors had come to fruition.
The minister said: "In recent days, we have begun to see the dawn at the end of the tunnel."
