Michelle Carter sentenced for texting Conrad Roy to commit suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for instigating her boyfriend’s suicide by texting and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, 20, will serve a 15-month sentence, which can be turned into a suspended sentence after the expiration of the sentence.
Carter was convicted of unintentional and unpremeditated murder in June by Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at Thursday’s hearing: “My family is heartbroken.
My son is my best friend."
While awaiting appeal, Carter was granted personal freedom.
She faces up to 20 years in prison, but her group believes she and Mr. Roy are mentally ill.
At the time of the sentencing, Carter stood, wearing red trousers and beige hoodies, his hands clasped, his eyes tearful, his eyes down.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
“She ended his life for living better for herself.
She was not responsible,” the prosecutor said.
"She has no remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a terrible consequence, and she feels very sorry."
However, Judge Lawrence Moniz said he did not find that her “age or maturity, or even her mental illness, would have any significant impact on her behavior.”
One prosecutor read a statement from Lynn Roy, a mother of Roy, saying, “I haven’t had a day without pain in losing my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of what I've done for me and me. I'm trying to stand with my sisters in all my pain that will stay with us forever," the statement said.
Mr Roy’s sister, Camdyn Roy, testified that she was “spiritually tramped” for realizing she would never be able to attend her brother’s wedding or become his child’s aunt.
“It’s a pain to lose someone who has been with me since I was born, and the rest of my life will be with that pain,” she said.
The case seems to set a legal precedent because the Massachusetts law does not require the prosecution of others to commit suicide.
In 2014, Roy was found dead of carbon monoxide poisoning in his car; Carter was 17 years old.
Carter’s text message revealed that the case drew national attention after she encouraged him to kill himself.
“There are many ways to hang yourself, jump, and stab yourself,” she said in several text messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was on vacation with his family.
The time before he committed suicide, she wrote: “You need to do this, Conrad, “All you have to do is start the generator and then you get freedom and happiness.”
Judge Moniz said Carter drew attention through Mr. Roy's death and ordered her not to profit from the case through any media.
There are differences of legal opinion in this case.
Amanda Knox, one of the few who defended Carter, was acquitted two years after she was charged with murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007.
Ms Knox, 30, said in an op-ed published in the Los Angeles Times: “Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not imprisonment.”
