How can radicalists learn to answer this question: “Whose streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrer was troubled.
On the first day of his trip to New York City, the St. Louiser sat in his rented bed with Audemarius and browsed Facebook on his mobile phone.
She stumbled upon a high school student post.
“The police have just killed an 18-year-old child, and the child is still lying in the street.”
She found that no one else had posted the message on the feed, and she was confused. She turned off Facebook and opened Twitter.
A @TheePharoah user keeps pushing her the dynamic time.
The St. Louis-area rapper tweeted about Michael Brown's death. Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man, was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown's body lying on the street with his body missing from life, and his body lay in the street for four hours.
"Crazy," thought Ferrer.
But for her and her community, death is nothing new.
She put down her phone and didn’t open Twitter again that night, reading about the gathering of people on Canfield Avenue.
There were police footage and people shouting photos, and a photo of a man who claimed to be Brown’s father, which read: “Ferguson police have just killed my unarmed son!”
She saw a message at the scene where a police officer stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another policeman raised his rifle and screamed: “I will kill all of you ... animals.”
“It’s not normal,” Ferrer recalled.
“This is not something we take for granted, and can be called a typical murder.”
At that moment, I felt a bit of a shudder.
I was angry and crying.
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father’s house and decided to travel to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrer and Ferguson over the next three years was the subject of a new documentary, “Whose Streets?”, which was released in theaters on August 11.
It’s a story about survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience from the perspective of people who live in this community and crowd the streets demanding answers.
When Ferrer and his daughter (wearing a floral dress and with a crowned accessory) driving to Ferguson, the two re-discussed the topic they had discussed countless times before that morning — “about the black experience and the black situation.”
“Do you remember when I taught you that black people had to fight for their faith?” she recalled.
“We’re going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, which is not right.
“I had to take her with me,” Ferrer said later.
“What happened today is the climax of everything in the past.
She wants to know, see, and rise from this.
Not only does she need to develop well in terms of activism and organization, but also to understand the different aspects of the black experience and the situation of black people, what we must do to achieve freedom and liberation.
Even though I had the privilege of providing her with the racist experiences she hadn’t experienced firsthand, she was no different from other black girls.
If I protect her in this matter, I feel like I'm hurting her."
Their first stop in Ferguson was located at a site opposite the police station of South Florida Road. The militants became their camp after the result of the eventual non-indictment of Officer Darren Wilson.
Ferrer and her daughter contacted a local business owner who made a bagged lunch.
They prepared bags and were responsible for passing them to the protesters.
Slowly, Ferrer began to form a new kind of activism.
“My activism changed completely after August 9,” she said, as she enrolled at Missouri State University’s St. Louis campus, she was president of the Society of Minority Nurses, focusing on the food justice and health disparities in the black community.
“I have no organizational experience.
That's how it all came about."
A few weeks later, Ferrer met with the film's co-director, Sabah Foleyan, during a night parade.
Foleyan said she and her photography director, Lucas Alvarado Falle, were “just trying to document” what happened.
Ferrell’s mind came up with the question: “Do you want to record or do you want to find a story that you can use?”
This skepticism stems from many of these cases: people — often white people — enter a community to benefit from their pain and tenacity.
As Fleyang explained in a recent interview, “We have heard that natives of Ferguson are not concentrating their voices, and we want to do it differently.”
Foleyan has been in contact with co-director Dimon Davis. Dimon Davis is a regional artist known for his activism against death row inmates.
His involvement led Ferrer, along with six other locals, to join the “Whose Streets?” project team, which remained in mind for several years after Brown’s shooting.
“This documentary is not about someone talking to us or talking to us, that’s what we’re talking to,” Davis said.
“I’m mainly concerned with how these characters are presented, because that’s how I’m presented.”
Although the goal is not to focus on Ferrer’s experience — but to show that the movement is “not about the messiah leader, but about community cohesion,” Foleyang said — it turns out that she is the most open to film participants.
The result, “Whose Street?” is a surprising record of Ferrer’s personal life, such as falling in love and getting married.
“I feel naked,” Ferrer laughed the first time he saw the finished product.
“But I understand that to do this work and humanize the Negro, there has to be a certain degree of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrer’s story reaffirms and repositions the role of black queer women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement’s three founders — who created #BlackLivesMatter on social media after the 2012 shooting of black teenager Trevorn Martin — were identified as queer.
“Black queer women in leadership have supported this movement in general,” Ferrer said, “because we’re constantly fighting on multiple fronts.”
Black queer women have to endure it all."
Foleyan agreed and mentioned that “this movement really has the support of black women and many black queer women.”
Because of her identity, Ferrer was chosen as the centerpiece of the film. However, she insisted that "this is not an affirmative action for things".
“She’s the one who inspires that kind of energy,” she said.
"Although she's on the front lines, it's no coincidence. Because in life at these crossroads, as a black queer woman, you have a lot to do.
Through the screen, you can feel her energy."
Meanwhile, in Ferguson, news cameras have long since disappeared, but tensions between the community and the police remain in race.
Ferrer was sentenced to more than two-and-a-half years on probation for trying to block the highway during a parade.
She described the socio-political atmosphere of the region she called home: “a mess.”
Still, since taking to the streets of Ferguson three years ago, she has stuck to the hymns she’s struggled to remember.
“We have a responsibility to fight for freedom.
We have a responsibility to win.
We must love each other and support each other.
We can't lose anything, except the shackles on our bodies."
