Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko said: "We will complete the roadmap of the World Anti-Doping Agency in the near future".
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitali Mutko said it would not take long to implement the remaining standards of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) for the restoration of the rights of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA).
“The implementation of the roadmap standard has reached a certain stage, and RUSADA has acquired the right to plan and test in cooperation with UKAD (UK Anti-Doping Agency).
The WADA roadmap has been updated in this regard,” Mutko said Thursday.
Deputy Prime Minister Mutko made the remarks in commenting on Part II of the WADA Roadmap, Compliance Regulations. This section sets out the criteria for restoring RUSADA rights and was recently posted on the organization's website.
According to Mutko, the standard does not contain anything that might cause concern to Russia.
He added, “Everything has to be announced and everything will be implemented.
The results will also be presented to the International Olympic Committee [IOC] and WADA in the near future.”
However, one of the criteria mentioned in the list is that the Russian Anti-Doping Agency must publicly accept the findings approved by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren on WADA’s support for doping incidents in national sports.
Speaking about the matter, Mutko said: “We are investigating and there is no doubt that our anti-doping system has failed.
All measures have already been implemented.
But there is no national plan behind it, and we will not admit that there is no such thing.”
Mutko responded to the words of Vitali Smirnov, head of Russia’s Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russian outlet RSport earlier in the day, Smirnov acknowledged the past problems with the Russian Anti-Doping Agency, but added: “We have said on various occasions many times that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report unconditionally,” Smirnov said.
After the doping scandal in November 2015, WADA suspended RUSADA’s right to perform doping inspections in Russia.
But in June, RUSADA was allowed to plan and coordinate testing this year under the supervision of international experts and UKAD.
WADA Director-General Olivia Negri, visiting the group’s headquarters in Moscow in July, said RUSADA was “moving in the right direction” in an effort to restore its rights.
