Amy Erret once wanted to investigate employee happiness at her e-commerce startup, but the survey didn’t work.
The responses received are often vague, unhelpful, and even worse, deceptive responses.
Even though she promised to take the form of anonymity, some employees still distrust the process.
Madison Reed, a San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company that runs 75 people, said she “has a lack of consistency and objectivity in the responses.”
So she called for help.
A new group of human resources startups has sprung up to help companies understand how employees feel.
They build and empower software specifically designed to measure employee engagement, allowing companies to conduct rapid polls for specific teams and population groups, provide anonymous and complaint hotlines for employees, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass executives and report directly to the board.
“Now, you can track your health with tools like Strava and Fitbit, but where is the company’s Fitbit?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint. The Glint software analytics tool is used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Erret said that in three years, she used Glint to gain more insights into what employees think and feel.
In addition to team-specific quick surveys and polls, Glint offers company heat maps, which units have the most complaints, and which managers approve low scores at a glance — which allows her to get a deep understanding of why.
Companies are beginning to realize that they must be proficient in controlling their workplace culture to avoid becoming the next Uber. Former Uber employees have previously published a blog post describing the harassment environment, and these speakers were punished by the company, and then Uber was caught in a scandal.
For startups like Glint, the company’s desire to oversee is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to financial technology analytics website Let’s Talk Payments, the global governance, regulatory, and compliance industry could be worth more than $11.87 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a start-up in Denver, Colorado, is dedicated to helping companies prevent and detect bad behavior, and they saw an increase in interest and activity in this area during Uber’s reputation damage earlier this year.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up to become a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized “diagnosis” surveys that collect confidential responses in real time and view heat maps of their problem areas.
Convercent also provides an anonymous SMS hotline for employees to report bad behavior.
If the chairman is implicated, the complaint will go directly to the board.
Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent, said: “The court of public opinion has usurped the power of regulators.
If a company is found to be ill-treated or unethical for employees, the company could face high consequences of consumer boycotts, employee churn and lawsuits, even if regulators don’t step in, Mr. Quinland said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain that spans more than 500 locations and employs more than 25,000 people, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees understand the work guidelines and procedures, providing an easy way to connect with the company’s headquarters.
Until then, if employees want to report the problem, they must find a company headquarters phone number or email, make a formal complaint, and hope that headquarters can take it seriously.
This is often a frightening and unsettling experience, says James Vitrano, general counsel for Ruby Tuesday, who doesn’t think there’s a good way to track down employee complaints.
But now that the company uses Convercent, it can more quickly identify and address issues that executives in remote offices, cities, or states did not know about — such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair wage behavior.
“I can get a closer, 360-degree view of the work experience,” said Vitrano, who is in charge of the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
“We are protecting our shareholders from employment lawsuits.”
Quinlan said that after the collapse of Andorran accounting firms because of the breach of ethical code of the Enron scandal, companies have paid more attention to ethics, values and employee engagement since 2002.
But it wasn’t until “social media went into their own world” that companies realized they couldn’t stop their revelations from spreading virally online.
“Before using technology to monitor ethics, people see hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent provide their software as a service and charge companies recurring fees for their product use.
This business model and business opportunity is supported by venture capitalists who have already supported both startups.
In February, Convercent raised $10 million in funding from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, with total capital rising to $47 million.
In November, Glint received $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners, with a total funding of $60 million.
Given the interconnectedness of companies, culture and venture capital, these investments are hardly surprising.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees have higher expectations of the workplace than before.
In a competitive market like Silicon Valley, high-paying water and interesting projects are just bets.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted, valued, and that their time is spent on a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to join the company, feel their voices being heard, and the work they do is beneficial, they’re more committed to making the company successful,” said Nina McCartney, LinkedIn’s vice president of global benefits and employee experience.
Investors pay off when their portfolio companies perform well; companies perform well when they are loyal and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no surprise they’ll be looking for financial support.
Workplace culture experts say it’s important to have employee engagement data.
However, this data is useless unless the company’s administrators take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can expect the company to be changing.
If the change doesn’t go fast enough, or if it doesn’t make a little bit of progress, it can lead to disappointment and disengage employees from the company.
Russell Ruth, head of consulting at business management firm Kott International, said: “If you want to seek 4,000 suggestions, you need to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations.” He has seen some companies over-residence in data collection.
“Because if you don’t follow up the whole time, the employee will think, ‘Did you really hear what I said?’
Do you care?
If you don’t care, why should I care?”
Emerson said Madison Reed now conducts monthly employee surveys and has been able to take action on the day Glint reports the problem.
After collecting feedback from employees about their frustration with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to solve problems by reorganizing her internal team and increasing communication training.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new insights into its employees, and in the long run they want to be able to make a shift in an industry known for high brain drain rates to better retain employees.
“If you’re not committed to creating a culture of transparency, you’re going to lose talent,” Vitrano says.
“If you lose talent, you lose customers.
And when you lose customers, you lose the company."
