Meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But the results of a new study show the opposite: a meat-rich diet with protein and dairy products can help relieve the symptoms associated with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease has a life impact for about 1.3 million Americans and about 300,000 Britons, leading to stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or hemorrhagic diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Researchers at the University of Washington typically recommend that patients avoid eating meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but researchers have found that the protein’s key amino acid, tryptophan, helps boost immune cell growth, and that these cells can improve the tolerance of the gut.
Lead researcher Dr Marco Colonna explained that immune cells patrol the intestines to ensure that harmful microbes hidden in food do not sneak into the body.
Maintain a balance between the cells that trigger inflammation and the cells that improve tolerance, protecting the body from damaging all kinds of sensitive and fragile tissue.
When the equilibrium state is too biased towards inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
In experiments, it was found that an immune-promoting cell appeared in mice carrying special bacteria.
Bacteria need tryptophan (one of the components of a protein) to form the appearance of a cell.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between a bacterial population (Lactobacterium Royce, which is a normal part of the gut microbiota) and the development of a cell population that promotes tolerance.
The more tryptophan mice consume in their diet, the more immune cells they have.
He suggested that if humans use the same approach, i.e., a combination of Lactobus lutyl and a tryptophol-rich diet, it may form a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment.
Postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, who studied an immune cell that improved tolerance, did not have another group of identical strains when she discovered that one group of studied mice had such cells, but the other group of the same strain was not raised separately.
She suspects that this difference is related to the gut microbiome of mice (referring to the communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract).
DNA sequencing of mouse cholesterol found that six bacterial populations were present in mice with immune cells, but not in mice without immune cells.
Rats are raised in a sterile environment, so they lack gut microbes and cannot appear in this immune cell, and the presence of Lactobacterium Lucilla produces immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers cultured Lactoblastin in a liquid and then transferred a small amount of bacteria-free fluid to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
This immune cell develops into a cell with tolerance.
When the active ingredient is purified from the liquid, it can be proved that the active ingredient is a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, called indoe-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the number of tryptophans in mice’s feed, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells was halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people, like mice, have the same cells that improve tolerance, and most of us have L. lutterilus in our gastrointestinal tract.
Whether humans can induce cell development by-tryphanide products from Lactobia L. lutylc in the body, as in experimental mice, is not yet known, but genetic defects related to tryptophan have been found in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
