China's household debt rate is close to the United States, more terrible than not being able to afford a home is not being able to pay the debt?
Recently, everyone is discussing what changes in real estate policy has recently, is it real estate policy to relax? land policy supply subject diversification, will the house price decline?
However, when we are worried about real estate prices, worried about macroeconomic regulation, and worried about the future trend of the real estate market, the People's Daily once again wrote, the last time we specifically discussed the "People's Daily" comment on the setting of real estate regulation, and now the "People's Daily" wrote an article on a more serious topic than not being able to afford to buy a house, is even if you can afford to buy a house, still have to get a debt?
Today, we’re going to talk about a bigger problem than buying a house: paying off the loan.
China's Growing Housing Debt Crisis
"People's Daily" published an opinion article on January 17, "Award and Loan: The Joy and Worry of Struggle Youth", according to the data of the article, in November 2017, the "China Deleveraging Process Report of the Third Quarter" released by the National Finance and Development Laboratory of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and the National Balance Sheet Research Center pointed out that the leverage ratio of the residential sector still continued to rise, from 47.4% in the second quarter of 2017 to 48.6% in the third quarter, up 1.3 percentage points, up 3.8 percentage points in the first three quarters of 2017.
The proportion of debt in the residential sector in the entire real economy has increased, and the leverage ratio has risen rapidly.
Relevant research shows that the debt of Chinese households in financial institutions is dominated by consumer loans, accounting for about two-thirds of the debt of residents, about twice the amount of operating loans.
Among them, in consumer loans, medium- and long-term loans, mainly housing loans account for about 80%, but from the incremental point of view, short-term consumer loans are growing faster than medium- and long-term loans.
In addition, China's household debt ratio only counts the total amount of credit received by the family sector from financial institutions, while Chinese families also have many private loans, including borrowing money from relatives and friends, and there is a large-scale hidden debt.
According to statistics from the Suning Institute of Finance, the leverage ratio of Chinese residents was only 3% in 1996 and only 18% in 2008, but the leverage ratio of residents has begun to show a rapid growth trend since 2008, doubling to 36.4% in just six years. By the third quarter of 2017, the leverage ratio of residents had reached 48.6%.
In May last year, HSBC released a survey of tens of thousands of respondents across nine countries.
The report is aimed at “millennial” young people (born between 1980 and 2000) in nine countries.
The report pointed out that China's 80-90s young people's homeownership rate is as high as 70%, far ahead of second-place Mexico (46%), which is also the United States' two-fold level of this indicator (35%).
The data tells us a high-probability problem that Chinese residents are probably unable to pay off their debt compared to the biggest potential “gray rhino” at this stage.
Why is the housing crisis the most serious problem?
As we have analyzed before, although we have been saying that China's housing prices are higher, compared with other countries in the world, China's housing ownership rate is actually quite high, so not so much about high house prices, I am afraid that the question for many friends is that you still have to get a loan?
Throughout the world's real estate market, China's real estate market has started late, and there has been no major real estate crisis except for Hainan, as we said before, but the origin of the 2008 world financial tsunami a decade ago was the real estate crisis in the United States.
The cause of the U.S. real estate crisis is blamed on two houses: Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
At that time, in the golden age of the United States, real estate companies sold their houses to low-income people in the United States at that time in order to expand sales, and when the U.S. economy was good, the real estate market was also thriving, but the good news was not long, and with the stagnation of growth in the US economy, it caused a decline in the income of home buyers, so a large amount of household consumption expenditure began to decline.
However, the current situation in the United States was an integral part of the financial assets and real estate assets of American household assets, and almost all the household assets of the low-income group in the United States were real estate, while the majority of the assets of the top 20% of the high-income group were financial assets, so the debt ratio of real estate in the poorer people in the United States was the higher.
A serious fact is that these people are buying houses when the economy is better, so the money paid for the mortgage is also calculated by their better income, when the income has declined, the pressure of the mortgage not only did not reduce or even because some subprime plans became floating and increased, so the real estate problems of these American families in this way gradually evolved into a real estate crisis.
Therefore, some people because the income is too low to pay the mortgage, so the bank began to recover the property, when the bank from the arrears of the buyers of the hands of the property, they will sell at a very low price, resulting in the region's house prices gradually decline, the process led to a further decline in house prices, the formation of a vicious circle, when the house prices fell to a certain extent, more and more buyers found that their home value has even been lower than their own loans, so there are more people to stop the repayment of mortgages, and caused more bad debts.
Thus, a huge vicious circle is formed:
“The economic downturn – the decline in income – some people can’t afford to pay off the mortgage – the bank sells the homes of the debtors at a low price – the house price falls – more people stop paying the mortgage – the bank sells it again – and the house price falls again...”
And the problem is not more than that, because the price of housing prices continue to fall, we stop the loan to the bank after you do not have debt, if the bank auction house to get the money is not yet you owe the bank loan, then you still need to pay back the money, simply put to say that you used the first payment of 600,000, the loan 2.4 million to buy a house worth 3 million, when the house fell to the house only worth 2 million, you no longer repay the house to the bank, after the bank auctioned the house, you not only lost their own debt of $ 600,000, you still owe the bank.
So, in one vicious cycle after another, the U.S. economy gradually collapsed, which eventually triggered the 2008 financial crisis in the United States.
Therefore, at this stage, China's household debt ratio level reached a high of 46.8% is a very need to be vigilant problem, this data is still lower than the level of developed countries, but the problem has begun to appear, the country from last year began to repeatedly emphasize the problem of deleveraging, this is a very prescient judgment, if the household debt ratio is allowed to continue to climb, it will inevitably lead to huge risks, so to prevent the emergence of financial risks.
So with the fact that the house is used for living, not for speculation, the state has accelerated the establishment of multiple measures such as multi-subject supply, multi-channel security, rent-purchase and mergers and acquisitions to further resolve potential risks.
For our individual families, we must give up real estate speculation, buy a house when the ability to do, to avoid their own family into a huge burden, only a reasonable assessment of their income and debt level is a healthy family wealth development path.
Author: Special researcher of Suning Financial Research Institute, financial columnist, financial commentator.
